Statistical Rethinking - Chapter 4 Questions

Question 1

The weights listed below were recorded in the !Kung cencus, but heights were not recorded for these individuals. Provide predicted heights and 89% intervals (either HPDI or PI) for each of these individuals. That is, fill in the tble below, using model-based predictions.

set.seed(89)
# Data for which we need to predict
test_data <- data.frame(
  individual = c(1,2,3,4,5),
  weight = c(46.95, 43.72, 64.78, 32.59, 54.63)
  )

# Create model parameters
flist <- alist(
  height ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
  mu <- a + b*weight.s, 
  a ~ dnorm(138, 100),
  b ~ dnorm(0, 10),
  sigma ~ dunif(0,50)
)

m4.1 <- map(flist, d)

prediction <- 0

for (i in test_data$individual){
  predicted_height_samples <- extract.samples(m4.1)$a + ((test_data[test_data$individual==i, ]$weight - mean_weight) * extract.samples(m4.1)$b / sd_weight)
  prediction_temp <- data.frame(
    individual = i,
    mean_predicted_height = mean(predicted_height_samples), 
    lower_quantile_89 = PI(predicted_height_samples, 0.89)[1],
    upper_quantile_89 = PI(predicted_height_samples, 0.89)[2]
  )
  if(length(prediction)==1){
    prediction <- prediction_temp
  }
  else{
    prediction <- rbind(prediction, prediction_temp)
  }
}

test_data <- merge(test_data, prediction, by="individual")
test_data

Question 2

Select out all the rows in the Howell1 data with ages below 18 years of age. If you do it right, you should end up with a new data frame with 192 rows in it.

  1. Fit a linear regression to these data, using map. Present and interpret the estimates. For every 10 units of increase in weight, how much taller does the model predict a child gets?
set.seed(89)
d_child <- d[d$age < 18,]

flist2 <- alist(
  height ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
  mu <- a + b*weight, 
  a ~ dnorm(50, 20),
  b ~ dnorm(4, 10),
  sigma ~ dunif(0,50)
)

m4.2 <- map(flist2, d_child)
mean(extract.samples(m4.2,10)$a)
## [1] 57.85178
# A child with 0 weight would hypothetically be around 58 units tall
mean(extract.samples(m4.2,10)$b)
## [1] 2.675135
# For every extra 10 units of weight, the child would be around 27 units higher
  1. Plot the raw data, with height on the vertical axis and weight on the horizontal axis. Superimpose the MAP regression line and 89% HPDI for the mean. Also superimpose the 89% HPDI for predicted heights.
weight.seq <- seq(from = 0, to = 50, by = 1)
mu <- link(m4.2, data=data.frame(weight = weight.seq))

Question 3

Suppose a colleague of yours, who works on allometry, glances at the practice problems just above. Your colleague exclaims, Thats silly. Everyone knows that its only the logarithm of body weight that scales with height! Lets take your colleagues advice and see what happens.

  1. Model the relationship between height (cm) and the natural logarithm of weight (log-kg). Use the entire Howell1 data frame, all 544 rows, adults and non-adults. Fit this model, using quadratic approximation: hi ~ Normal(mu(i); sigma) mu(i) = a + b log(wi) a ~ Normal(178; 100) b ~ Normal(0; 100) sigma ~ Uniform(0; 50) where h(i) is the height of individual i and w(i) is the weight (in kg) of individual i. The function for computing a natural log in R is just log. Can you interpret the resulting estimates?
